        "id": 1466,
        "name": "Christophe Chevalier",
        "username": "KrzysFR",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/krzysfr/{size}/43_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-06-14T16:49:29.989Z",
        "cooked": "<p>There a settable options on the Database handle for the Machine and Datacenter ID.</p>\n<p>I have configured two set of fdb process with two <code>datacenter_id</code> (<code>DC01</code> and <code>DC02</code>*), but left untouched the <code>machine_id</code> in <code>foundationdb.conf</code>.</p>\n<p>Looking at the output of <code>status json</code> for one of the nodes, I see in the <code>locality</code> object:</p>\n<p>So I can safely assume that for the datacenter id, I can pass the string \u201cDC01\u201d (or \u201cDC02\u201d). But the machine id looks like a hash from some string unique to the host.</p>\n<p>How can a local application, running on the same host, know about that ID to set the corresponding option on the database handle?</p>\n<p>Do I need to explicitly set the <code>machine_id</code> in the <code>foundationdb.conf</code> of each host to a known value (probably using the host name), so that the application can also set the same value?</p>\n<p>What would happen if an application would set a datacenter or machine id option with a value that is not valid anymore ?</p>\n<p>I\u2019m looking for a way to have each client automatically prefer the local node (if there is one present) without having to check out of band to get the correct value.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 2,
        "updated_at": "2018-06-14T16:49:29.989Z",
